                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/1094: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-04-11T18:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 11, 1928—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 11—10:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>223. Legation’s 193, March 29, 5 [<hi rend="italic">8</hi>] p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>At meeting of diplomatic body, April 2, Japanese Minister stated that on
                        March 26 his Government had received a note from the Soviet Ambassador in
                        Tokyo relating to the attitude of the Soviet Government towards
                        participation in the arms embargo agreement. Tenor of the note was substance
                        as reported in the Legation’s telegram above mentioned. Japanese Minister
                        said his Government purposed to make further representations to the Soviet
                        Government upon the matter.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Copy to Tokyo by mail.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
